article.headline: Taurasi leads Mercury with 27 points
article.linkText: Storm beat Mercury for third straight win
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Usually, the Seattle Storm are led by defending
WNBA scoring champion Lauren Jackson. The Phoenix Mercury weren't
counting on Seattle's other big player.

Six-foot-4 Janell Burse scored 21 points, while 6-5 Lauren
Jackson added 12 points and 14 rebounds to carry the Storm past the
Mercury 78-67 Thursday night.

"Yeah, 44 points in the paint -- our objective coming in was we
didn't think anybody could contain Lauren," said Seattle coach
Anne Donovan. "Well, they did. They had two or three people
containing Lauren and, in the meantime, Janell got busy."

The defending WNBA champion Storm, who have won three straight
since an opening-night loss, outrebounded Phoenix 37-32 and scored
44 points in the lane to 24 by Phoenix. The rebounding difference
was 32-21 when Seattle opened the big lead halfway through the
second half.

"We just did not get the job done inside and you can't do that
against a team with an inside presence like the Storm and expect to
win," said Phoenix coach Carrie Graf.

Burse, who averaged five points a game last season and seven a
game so far in 2005, was 8-of-11 from the field, all from inside 5
feet. That wasn't what Donovan had seen in the first three games of
the year.

"Not so much in games, we see it in practice every day, so we
were waiting for it to click for her in a game," Donovan said.
"So it's nice it finally came."

But Burse wasn't as impressed in her game as you would think.

"I feel like there are some things that I could have done
better," she said. "It wasn't like I played the best game of my
life tonight. I made a couple of mistakes. [I've] just got to keep
at it."

The Storm went on a 16-5 run early in the second half to open a
15-point lead. Phoenix never got closer than seven the rest of the
night.

Diana Taurasi led the Mercury (1-4) with 27 points and five
assists.

"We come out and play very well for stretches at a time," said
Taurasi. "Then we have these two- or three-minute lapses and when
you look up at the scoreboard, we're down by 11. The sooner that we
can get that problem fixed, the sooner that we can get this team
rolling."

Sue Bird added 17 points and six assists and Betty Lennox scored
14 for the Storm, who led 39-34 at halftime.
